arch:note.arch:string: The purpose of the daily journal was to record the activities taking place in a trench each day. This included which loci were excavated, how and why loci were excavated and the ongoing impressions of the relationships among loci. It should be noted that journals record the actions, impressions and ideas of trench supervisors during the excavations. They are not, therefore, the final interpretations or syntheses of the emerging data.

arch:internalDocument.arch:string:
August 18, 2001

Area F

Trench 7

Katie Smith

Today we began by preparing L7005 for a spider shot. After we had articulate the surface, Andy thought another spider would be a good idea to record the most extensive surface we uncovered this season in F7 in addition to the fact that this surface was sealed by surfaces 7010 and 7040. Since we were taking photos, we went ahead and took all of the closing loci photos, section photos, and trench overview shots.

After all the photos were finished, we removed surface L7005. We took 4 soil chemical samples and plotted them all on Day Plan B for today. We also took one soil sample for flotation. In the surface we found what may be a pestle and KT'd it as 7311 and we also found a small grindstone that was KT'd as 7312.

While the workmen were removing the surface, I took out the remainder of the rock conglomerate in 7014. It is interesting to note that there was a lot of pottery mixed up with the large stones. After L7014 was closed, I took down the other half of L7039, which was the locus of concentrated virgin soil. Nothing was found Friday when it was sectioned and there was nothing to not today as I excavated it, so I closed this locus.

I collected all of the broken cranium pieces from the burial 7028. They were KT'd as 7315. There was not enough time to excavate it this season and these pieces would not have survived the off-season exposed as they were.

Likewise, I collected all of the visible surface pottery from fill layer L7032, but no actual excavation took place.

After "cleaning-up", I opened 3 new loci that had become apparent. In the northern part of the trench, I assigned what looks to be a surface as L7044. It had a lot of small pebbles, some cobbles, and some pottery. It is directly beneath what was surface L7029. I also opened a locus for a pit that appears to cut this new surface (7044). This pit is now L7042 and is equal to pit L7021. After taking down the elevation in the fill layer, it is clear that it was not fully excavated at the time I closed it. There is another pit in the center of the western half. It is large in diameter around 1.25m, but we will be unable to excavate it this season.

These last three loci were opened and then closed with all the other remaining loci in this trench. We took final elevations and closed for the season:(
